title: For Sale:  Walther PP Size Holster East German Military & Police Brown Leather Flap Type for 1001 Pistol PPK PPKS CZ50 CZ70 Fits Many 32 380 and 9x18 Makarov Caliber Pistols
postcontent:
Our # GLMDL

This listing is for ONE holster from the same lot showing in the photos. Buyers, however, may take any number of extras at the same per-holster price and with no additional shipping charges. From very light duty in the Cold War Days of Communist East Germany comes these attractive, protective and eminently serviceable leather holsters originally designed for East German Police Pistols that were Walther PP knock-offs. They will also fit similarly sized CZ Pistols, models CZ24, CZ50, and CZ70. They fit the single action Zastava Yugoslavian made M70 in .32 ACP. Beretta models 1934, 1935, 70, and 71 fit well in this holster, and that goes for the 70 clones made by Tangfolio and imported by FIE and Excam, including models TA380, E380, E32, and E22. Measurements will accommodate a pistol whose length measures up to 6 1/2 inches from its muzzle to its grip frame strut beneath its hammer; with a slide thickness of up to 1 inch; and with a muzzle height of up to 1 1/4 inches measured from the top of the front sight to the bottom of the slide. The pistol’s height from the top of the rear sight to the floorplate bottom of an in-battery magazine should not exceed 4 3/4 inches. Manufacturer on these was probably the State Factory in Baden, East Germany. Construction is smooth grained dark brown leather outer, with natural soft suede type finish inner. Stitching is close looped cotton twine. Strap is eye type, secured by a two piece aluminum alloy stud. Belt loop is single 1 7/8 inches wide secured by six alloy rivets, and will accommodate up to a 2 inch wide belt. This is a well made holster that will protect a pistol very well, and its styling is distinctively European. Surface wear is minimal, and we do not believe these served on duty for more than 2 or 3 years, if that long. Most specimens are marked on the inner flap by the MDL, the East German Ministry of the Interior in loose translation, certifying its fitness for duty use. We estimate these holsters were manufactured in the mid 1970s to early 1980s. We’re offering specimens from the photo lot each for only $ 24.00. >>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>>> Grips, Magazines, slings, holsters, scopes, mounts, parts & most any small light items, entire accessory orders only $10.00 USPS Priority Mail with Adult Signature, total shipping no matter how many a person buys. title: For Sale/Trade:  "1985" Prototype Silhouette EBMM Electric Guitar (Ernie Ball Music Man)
postcontent:
Own a "one-of-a-kind" American Classic, made in California.  This gorgeous treasure from yesterday plays an amazing tune, and can be yours!  Whether you are a future "Juke Box Hero," have your gig together, or an expert rock star, you deserve an amazing unique guitar.  This axe is fit for any rock star future, current, or past!

Sure, you could buy a cheap-o guitar.  Or you could buy a production piece, one-of-many-thousands.   Or one with a signature (but who cares about signatures -- which can be faked?!).  These might be satisfying to you. 

But come on.  You work hard, so you deserve to spend your money on an amazing rare guitar. 
Walk with me for a minute.  It was the mid-1980s.  Ernie Ball had been in business since the early 1970s, but was still a very young company, and experimenting with various guitars.  Along came the Silhouette design around 1986-87. 

And here's where this guitar comes into the picture.  It's an authentic circa-1985 prototype EBMM Silhouette, as confirmed by EBMM customer service.  Guitar has been inspected by two guitar shop owners and is in excellent condition and sounds amazing.  There are a few tiny cosmetic character marks to note:  a few small nicks in the paint finish, the input jack has a small bend, a small piece of tape was removed near the input, and the fretboard shows some wear.  This guitar has character, style, and class like a fine old sports car or a fine wine in storage.  The aged paint design has created a very unique cracking appearance all throughout the paint under the finish, and the sunburst orange paint looks stunning.  There are no apparent cracks, bows, or structural damage to the guitar, inside or out.  Excellent working condition.  New strings recently installed. 

Famous people that have used EBMMs: John Petrucci (Dream Theater, Liquid Tension Experiment, solo artist), Ronnie Wood (The Rolling Stones), Eddie Van Halen (Van Halen), John Fogerty (Creedence Clearwater Revival), Mike Einziger (Incubus), Pino Palladino (Paul Young), Dave "Phoenix" Farrell (Linkin Park), Cliff Williams (AC/DC), John Myung (Dream Theater), John Glascock (Jethro Tull), John Deacon (Queen), Tim Commerford (Rage Against the Machine, Audioslave), Paul D'Amour (Tool), Dave "Phoenix" Farrell (Linkin Park), and a long list of others. 

See EBMM Wiki for more information. 

Per EBMM, Silhouettes are known for offset double cutaway alder, ash or poplar body, aluminum-lined pickguard, bolt-on maple neck, 24-fret maple or rosewood fingerboard with dot inlay, strings-through bridge, 4/2-per-side Schaller tuners, chrome hardware, two single coil and one humbucker DiMarzio pickups (three single coil and two humbucker pickup configurations were options until 1998), volume/tone control, five-way switch, available in Black, Natural, Sunburst, Trans. Blueburst, Trans. Teal, Trans. Red, or White finish, mfg. 1987-present.

Holding this guitar feels just perfect.  Own a piece of history.
